They have no compunction about exercising it even in instances where their lives and the lives of their children are in danger because the husband simply won’t accept it, or because he’s incapable of advancing funding for the children’s education and maintenance. I, who have divorced twice and whose children are a source of joy to me, agree with them.

Just watch what happens after dark: the streets, where young women and adolescent girls measure their personal and sexual aptitudes by the number of sexual encounters they have in front of strangers, take on a different face. They have only one rule: a man who is drunk can pick them up, or else, they do the picking up. The real “operation” starts here – but only in Chadale, or venues with a young clientèle. In the larger cities, sexual freedom is tempered by respect for a woman’s dignity. Here again, the rule is clear: “forbidden” – immorality – is abundant, especially in the capital. But there is still an official shield – Islam – paddling women down the rapids of concupiscence and granting them some rudimentary cautions.

In any case, “sex sells” – especially when it’s sold under the guise of “development”! Here, I think of One Teaspoon of Salt or How I Got Rid of My Baggage, a film by K. Gleytha Ponferrada, made in Comoros Island.
